```{r setup, include=FALSE}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = FALSE, message = FALSE, warning = FALSE)

# 載入所需套件
library(tidyverse)   # 數據處理 + ggplot2 畫圖
library(scales)      # 格式化數字（例如百分比）
library(knitr)       # 生成整齊嘅表格
library(kableExtra)  # 美化表格
library(lubridate)   # 處理日期
library(corrplot)    # 畫 correlation heatmap
library(gridExtra)   # 將多個圖並排顯示
```

```{r load-data}
# 讀入數據
df <- read_csv("Buy_Now_Pay_Later_BNPL_CreditRisk_Dataset.csv")

# 將 default_flag 轉成 factor（分類變數），方便之後建模
df <- df %>%
  mutate(
    default_flag = factor(default_flag, levels = c(0, 1),
                          labels = c("No Default", "Default")),
    employment_type  = factor(employment_type),
    product_category = factor(product_category),
    location         = factor(location),
    customer_segment = factor(customer_segment),
    bnpl_installments = factor(bnpl_installments),
    transaction_date = mdy(transaction_date)   # 轉成日期格式
  )
```

---

# Section 1: Dataset Overview

```{r dataset-overview}
# 製作一個基本 overview 表格
overview <- tibble(
  Item        = c("Total Records", "Total Variables", "Defaulted Users",
                  "Non-Defaulted Users", "Default Rate", "Missing Values"),
  Value       = c(
    format(nrow(df), big.mark = ","),
    ncol(df),
    format(sum(df$default_flag == "Default"), big.mark = ","),
    format(sum(df$default_flag == "No Default"), big.mark = ","),
    paste0(round(mean(df$default_flag == "Default") * 100, 1), "%"),
    "None"
  )
)

kable(overview, caption = "Table 1: Dataset Overview",
      booktabs = TRUE, align = c("l", "r")) %>%
  kable_styling(latex_options = c("hold_position"), full_width = FALSE)
```

**Interpretation:** The dataset contains 10,345 BNPL transactions across 17 variables. Overall, 39.1% of users defaulted on their repayments — a meaningful proportion that underscores the credit risk challenge in BNPL services.

---

# Section 2: Descriptive Statistics of Numerical Variables

```{r descriptive-stats}
# 選出數值型變數，計算各種統計量
num_vars <- df %>%
  select(age, monthly_income, credit_score, purchase_amount,
         repayment_delay_days, missed_payments,
         debt_to_income_ratio, risk_score, app_usage_frequency)

desc_stats <- num_vars %>%
  summarise(across(everything(), list(
    Mean   = ~round(mean(.), 2),
    Median = ~round(median(.), 2),
    SD     = ~round(sd(.), 2),
    Min    = ~round(min(.), 2),
    Max    = ~round(max(.), 2)
  ))) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything(),
               names_to  = c("Variable", "Statistic"),
               names_sep = "_(?=[^_]+$)") %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Statistic, values_from = value)

kable(desc_stats,
      caption = "Table 2: Descriptive Statistics of Numerical Variables",
      booktabs = TRUE, align = c("l", rep("r", 5))) %>%
  kable_styling(latex_options = c("hold_position", "scale_down"))
```

**Interpretation:** Key observations from the descriptive statistics:

- **Credit Score** ranges from 300 to 850, with a mean of 448 — skewed toward the lower end, suggesting many users have below-average creditworthiness.
- **Monthly Income** is highly right-skewed (mean = \$35,053 vs. median = \$23,801), indicating a small number of high-income users pulling the average up.
- **Repayment Delay Days** averages 8.7 days, with some users delaying up to 33 days.
- **Missed Payments** averages just over 1 per user, but ranges up to 7.

