# Section 3: Target Variable Distribution

```{r target-distribution, fig.cap="Figure 1: Distribution of Default Status", fig.width=5, fig.height=4}
df %>%
  count(default_flag) %>%
  mutate(pct = n / sum(n),
         label = paste0(comma(n), "\n(", percent(pct, accuracy = 0.1), ")")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = default_flag, y = n, fill = default_flag)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.5, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text(aes(label = label), vjust = -0.3, size = 4, fontface = "bold") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("No Default" = "#2196F3", "Default" = "#F44336")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma, limits = c(0, 7500)) +
  labs(title  = "Distribution of Default Status",
       x = "Default Status", y = "Number of Users") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
```

**Interpretation:** The dataset is moderately imbalanced — 61% of users did not default, while 39% did. This imbalance is not severe enough to ignore, but should be addressed during modelling (e.g., using SMOTE or class weighting) to prevent the model from being biased toward predicting non-defaults.

