# Section 4: Default Rate by Employment Type

```{r employment-default, fig.cap="Figure 2: Default Rate by Employment Type", fig.width=6, fig.height=4}
df %>%
  group_by(employment_type) %>%
  summarise(
    total   = n(),
    default = sum(default_flag == "Default"),
    rate    = default / total
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(employment_type, -rate), y = rate, fill = employment_type)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.5, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text(aes(label = percent(rate, accuracy = 0.1)),
            vjust = -0.4, fontface = "bold", size = 4) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent, limits = c(0, 0.6)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
  labs(title = "Default Rate by Employment Type",
       x = "Employment Type", y = "Default Rate") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
```

**Interpretation:** Unemployed users (48.7%) and Students (48.6%) have nearly **double** the default rate of Self-Employed users (26.2%) and significantly higher than Salaried workers (32.7%). This is intuitive — users with unstable or no income face greater difficulty repaying BNPL installments. BNPL providers should consider stricter credit checks or lower credit limits for these groups.

---

# Section 5: Default Rate by Customer Segment

```{r segment-default, fig.cap="Figure 3: Default Rate by Customer Risk Segment", fig.width=6, fig.height=4}
df %>%
  group_by(customer_segment) %>%
  summarise(
    total   = n(),
    default = sum(default_flag == "Default"),
    rate    = default / total
  ) %>%
  mutate(customer_segment = factor(customer_segment,
                                   levels = c("Low Risk", "Medium Risk", "High Risk"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = customer_segment, y = rate, fill = customer_segment)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.5, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text(aes(label = percent(rate, accuracy = 0.1)),
            vjust = -0.4, fontface = "bold", size = 4) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent, limits = c(0, 0.8)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Low Risk" = "#4CAF50",
                                "Medium Risk" = "#FF9800",
                                "High Risk" = "#F44336")) +
  labs(title = "Default Rate by Customer Risk Segment",
       x = "Customer Segment", y = "Default Rate") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
```

**Interpretation:** The risk segmentation system shows strong predictive validity. Low Risk users default at only 4.5%, Medium Risk at 29.2%, and High Risk users at 49.0%. This confirms that the `customer_segment` variable is a meaningful predictor and should be included in the predictive model. However, the large proportion of users classified as High Risk (73%) warrants attention — overly conservative segmentation may limit BNPL business growth.

