# Section 6: Credit Score Distribution by Default Status

```{r credit-score-dist, fig.cap="Figure 4: Credit Score Distribution by Default Status", fig.width=7, fig.height=4}
ggplot(df, aes(x = credit_score, fill = default_flag)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 30, alpha = 0.7, position = "identity", colour = "white") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("No Default" = "#2196F3", "Default" = "#F44336"),
                    name = "Default Status") +
  labs(title = "Credit Score Distribution by Default Status",
       x = "Credit Score", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.position = "top")
```

**Interpretation:** Users who defaulted tend to cluster at the lower end of the credit score spectrum (300–500), while non-defaulters show a wider and slightly higher distribution. This validates the use of `credit_score` as a predictor — lower credit scores are associated with higher default risk in BNPL contexts, consistent with traditional lending practices.

