# Section 7: Missed Payments & Repayment Delay vs. Default

```{r missed-delay, fig.cap="Figure 5: Missed Payments and Repayment Delay by Default Status", fig.width=8, fig.height=4}
p1 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = default_flag, y = missed_payments, fill = default_flag)) +
  geom_boxplot(show.legend = FALSE, outlier.alpha = 0.3) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("No Default" = "#2196F3", "Default" = "#F44336")) +
  labs(title = "Missed Payments", x = "", y = "Number of Missed Payments") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

p2 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = default_flag, y = repayment_delay_days, fill = default_flag)) +
  geom_boxplot(show.legend = FALSE, outlier.alpha = 0.3) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("No Default" = "#2196F3", "Default" = "#F44336")) +
  labs(title = "Repayment Delay (Days)", x = "", y = "Delay in Days") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)
```

**Interpretation:** Both missed payments and repayment delay days are clearly higher among defaulters. Defaulters have a notably higher median number of missed payments and tend to delay repayments longer. These are strong behavioural indicators of default risk and are likely to be among the most important predictors in any classification model.

