# Section 8: Debt-to-Income Ratio vs. Default

```{r dti-default, fig.cap="Figure 6: Debt-to-Income Ratio by Default Status", fig.width=6, fig.height=4}
ggplot(df, aes(x = default_flag, y = debt_to_income_ratio, fill = default_flag)) +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.6, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.1, fill = "white", show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("No Default" = "#2196F3", "Default" = "#F44336")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent) +
  labs(title = "Debt-to-Income Ratio by Default Status",
       x = "Default Status", y = "Debt-to-Income Ratio") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
```

**Interpretation:** The violin plot reveals that defaulters tend to have a higher debt-to-income ratio than non-defaulters. Users spending a larger proportion of their income on debt repayments are naturally more vulnerable to missing BNPL payments. This variable is an important financial health indicator that BNPL providers can use in real-time credit decisioning.

