# Section 9: Default Rate by Product Category

```{r product-default, fig.cap="Figure 7: Default Rate by Product Category", fig.width=7, fig.height=4}
df %>%
  group_by(product_category) %>%
  summarise(
    total   = n(),
    default = sum(default_flag == "Default"),
    rate    = default / total
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(product_category, -rate), y = rate, fill = product_category)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.5, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text(aes(label = percent(rate, accuracy = 0.1)),
            vjust = -0.4, fontface = "bold", size = 4) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent, limits = c(0, 0.55)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel1") +
  labs(title = "Default Rate by Product Category",
       x = "Product Category", y = "Default Rate") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
```

**Interpretation:** Default rates across product categories are relatively similar, ranging from 37.7% (Sports) to 41.0% (Fashion). While Fashion purchases show a slightly higher default rate, the differences are not dramatic. This suggests that product category alone is a weak predictor of default — the nature of the purchase matters less than the financial profile of the buyer.

