# Section 12: Monthly Transaction Volume Over Time

```{r time-trend, fig.cap="Figure 10: Monthly Transaction Volume and Default Rate Over Time", fig.width=8, fig.height=4}
df %>%
  mutate(month = floor_date(transaction_date, "month")) %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(
    transactions = n(),
    default_rate = mean(default_flag == "Default")
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = month)) +
  geom_col(aes(y = transactions), fill = "#90CAF9", alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_line(aes(y = default_rate * max(transactions) / max(default_rate)),
            colour = "#F44336", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(aes(y = default_rate * max(transactions) / max(default_rate)),
             colour = "#F44336", size = 2) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "Number of Transactions",
    labels = comma,
    sec.axis = sec_axis(
      ~ . * max(df %>% group_by(floor_date(transaction_date, "month")) %>%
                  summarise(r = mean(default_flag == "Default")) %>% pull(r)) /
        max((df %>% mutate(m = floor_date(transaction_date, "month")) %>%
               count(m))$n),
      name = "Default Rate",
      labels = percent
    )
  ) +
  scale_x_date(date_labels = "%b %Y", date_breaks = "3 months") +
  labs(title = "Monthly Transaction Volume and Default Rate Over Time",
       x = "Month") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
  theme(plot.title  = element_text(face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        axis.title.y.right = element_text(colour = "#F44336"),
        axis.title.y.left  = element_text(colour = "#1565C0"))
```

**Interpretation:** Transaction volumes are relatively stable across the observation period (2023–2024), with no dramatic seasonal spikes. The default rate (red line) also remains broadly consistent over time, hovering around 39%. This stability suggests the dataset captures a representative, steady-state snapshot of BNPL behaviour, making it well-suited for building a generalizable predictive model.

